{"timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:35:15.093Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"call_cw8M9rhHL7TIqBJoSLOJZUpH","output":"Chunk ID: 6a2786\nWall time: 0.4037 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1825\nOutput:\n{\"baseRefOid\":\"6ad728f1e880ed376f640a5348e95e135b1d5610\",\"headRefOid\":\"7227f7483451e1c1745748c25cde35320a968467\",\"mergeStateStatus\":\"DIRTY\",\"reviewDecision\":\"REVIEW_REQUIRED\",\"reviews\":[{\"id\":\"PRR_kwDOR9SkY878eDyd\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"Soph\"},\"authorAssociation\":\"MEMBER\",\"body\":\"EDIT: I don't know today was the day when Claude decided to just post a review instead of letting me just read it locally. 🤦 \\r\\n\\r\\n----\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\nThanks for tackling this. Nice that the `Conn` interface lands cleanly across the strategies and tests — the bulk of the diff is mechanical, easy to follow. Below are the things I'd want resolved before this merges.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Blocking\\r\\n\\r\\n### `SSHConn` breaks on the second `PostRPCStreamBody` call (i.e. protocol v2 + most batched flows)\\r\\n\\r\\n`SSHConn.PostRPCStreamBody` runs a single goroutine that closes `conn.stdin` via `defer` once it finishes copying the body (`internal/gitproto/ssh.go:118-123`). The remote `git-upload-pack` / `git-receive-pack` sees EOF on stdin and exits, leaving `stdout` at EOF too. There is no logic to spawn another `ssh` process; subsequent calls on the same `SSHConn` write to a closed pipe and read EOF.\\r\\n\\r\\nThat is a problem because git-sync routinely makes more than one RPC per connection:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Protocol v2 source (the default `auto` path).** `ListSourceRefs` does one `RequestInfoRefs` (capabilities) then `PostRPC` for `ls-refs` (`internal/gitproto/refs.go:157`). Later, `FetchPack` / `FetchToStore` does another `PostRPCStream` for `fetch` (`internal/gitproto/fetch.go:133/192/239`). That is 2× `PostRPCStreamBody` on the same source `SSHConn` — the second one will fail.\\r\\n- **Batched bootstrap.** `bstrap.Execute` calls `FetchPack` and `FetchCommitGraph` repeatedly (`internal/strategy/bootstrap/bootstrap.go:140`, `:500`, `:672`, `:990`) and pushes via `PushPack` / `PushCommands` repeatedly (`:155`, `:265`, `:312`, `:405`, `:476`, `:482`, `:514`).\\r\\n- **Incremental relay with both updates and tag-creates** (`internal/strategy/incremental/incremental.go:59` and `:78`).\\r\\n- **Replicate with both updates and deletes** (`internal/strategy/replicate/replicate.go:65` then `:79`).\\r\\n\\r\\nSo the only flow this PR safely handles is \\\"v1 source → exactly one fetch → exactly one push\\\". I suspect the happy-path testing went through v1 (or against a server that didn't negotiate v2 over SSH); GitHub does negotiate v2 on SSH, so anything against `github.com:foo/bar.git` with the default `--protocol=auto` should be hitting this.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe fix that aligns with how vanilla git works over SSH is one `ssh` exec per logical RPC: `RequestInfoRefs` and each `PostRPCStreamBody` should each spawn their own `ssh ... git-upload-pack <path>` (with `GIT_PROTOCOL=version=2` for v2 calls) rather than sharing a single long-lived process. That also fixes the second issue below for free.\\r\\n\\r\\nEither way, please add an integration test that exercises `--protocol=v2` end-to-end over SSH against a real `git-upload-pack`/`git-receive-pack` (a `sshd` test fixture or a `git+ssh://` URL pointing at a local `bin/ssh-shim`) — it's the only way to keep this from regressing.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Stats / progress / `--progress` are silently broken for SSH\\r\\n\\r\\n`syncer.assignNewConn` skips `instrumentHTTPClient` for ssh, so `statsCollector.Sides` never sees source/target byte counts. That makes `--stats`, the throughput line, and the live `--progress` ticker no-ops on SSH (the ticker checks side bytes; with zero bytes it stays blank). `--show-stats` will print zero bytes for both sides.\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you want to ship SSH without the progress flag wired up, that is a defensible scope cut for a first PR — but please surface it explicitly: at minimum log a one-liner via `notice` when a session has any SSH endpoint and `cfg.Progress` or `cfg.ShowStats` is on, so users don't think their throughput is \\\"0 B/s\\\". Or wire counting at the `io.ReadCloser` layer in `SSHConn` itself, which would be roughly the same shape as `countingRoundTripper` but at the stream boundary.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Should fix\\r\\n\\r\\n### `errBuf` is read concurrently with `cmd.Stderr` writes — data race\\r\\n\\r\\n`conn.errBuf` is a plain `bytes.Buffer` assigned as `conn.cmd.Stderr` (`ssh.go:69`) and then read on the error path while the `ssh` process may still be running and writing to it (`ssh.go:95`). `bytes.Buffer` is explicitly not safe for concurrent use; `go test -race` should flag this. Either capture stderr through a `*safeBuffer` (mutex-guarded `Write`/`String`) or only read it after `cmd.Wait()` has returned.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Default `git@` user\\r\\n\\r\\n`if conn.EndpointURL.User == nil { destination = \\\"git@\\\" + destination }` (`ssh.go:55-59`). This silently overrides `~/.ssh/config` `User` directives. If a user has `Host git.internal.example` → `User=gitea` in their ssh config, this code forces `git@git.internal.example` and the server will reject. Vanilla `git clone git.internal.example:foo/bar.git` would honor the ssh config because git does not inject a username.\\r\\n\\r\\nDrop the `git@` default and just pass the host (or leave the `user@` form only when the URL had explicit user info). Let `ssh` resolve the user from its own config.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Context dropped in `PostRPCStreamBody`\\r\\n\\r\\n`func (conn *SSHConn) PostRPCStreamBody(_ context.Context, ...)` (`ssh.go:112`). The `ctx` from `RequestInfoRefs` is what's controlling the `exec.Cmd`, so cancelling the per-fetch ctx mid-stream won't kill the ssh process or unblock a stuck `io.Copy`. The HTTP transport honors per-call ctx via `http.NewRequestWithContext`. If you go with one-process-per-RPC (recommended above), this fixes itself; otherwise wire the ctx through (`context.AfterFunc(ctx, func(){ conn.cmd.Process.Kill() })` or similar).\\r\\n\\r\\n## Nits\\r\\n\\r\\n- `internal/gitproto/conn.go:17` — comment says `// EndpointUrl returns ...` but the method is `Endpoint()`. Update the doc comment.\\r\\n- `internal/gitproto/smarthttp.go:93` — typo introduced in the `ProgressOut` doc comment: `plug in af coordinated writer` → `plug in a coordinated writer`.\\r\\n- `syncer.assignNewConn(conn *gitproto.Conn, ...)` (pointer-to-interface) is awkward. The idiomatic shape is `func newConn(...) (gitproto.Conn, error)` and let the caller assign. Same shape works for both source and target sites.\\r\\n- `SSHConn.Close()` nils `cmd` but leaves `stdin`/`stdout` populated. Either zero them too or document that `SSHConn` is single-use.\\r\\n- The hand-rolled pkt-line re-encoding in `RequestInfoRefs` (`fmt.Fprintf(&buf, \\\"%04x%s\\\", len(payload)+4, payload)`) reinvents what `EncodePacket` (or `FormatPktLine`) already does in this package. Reuse the shared helper, and consider whether protocol-v2 delim (`0001`) packets need to round-trip through here as well.\\r\\n- `BatchMode=yes` is a sensible default but worth a one-line note in the README / SSH docs: it disables host-key-acceptance prompts, so first-time hosts will fail until they're in `known_hosts`. Mention `-o StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new` as the workaround if appropriate.\\r\\n\\r\\nHappy to look again once the multi-RPC story is sorted.\",\"submittedAt\":\"2026-05-06T11:44:40Z\",\"includesCreatedEdit\":false,\"reactionGroups\":[],\"state\":\"COMMENTED\",\"commit\":{\"oid\":\"7227f7483451e1c1745748c25cde35320a968467\"}}]}\n"}}
